 popular liberalism and humanitarianism. It will appeal to scholars and general readers interested in the origins and significance of consumerism across a range of disciplines, including social and cultural history, literary studies, historical sociology and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConsumption (Economics)zGreat Britain. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Consumer Behavior.2bisacsh  aAndover cannibalism.  aAnti-Corn Law League.  aCharles Dickens.  aChartism.  aNew Poor Law.  aResponsible consumption and production.  aZero hunger.  acapitalist consumerism.  aconsumer politics.  afree trade.  ahunger.  aliberal consumerism.  amiddle-class excess.  amodern consumerism.  apopular liberalism.  apopular politics.  apopular radicalism.  aworking-class scarcity.1 aGurney, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610182240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101822/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles